The glass warps slightly under your touch, as though the surface is not solid but liquid.
The glass is utterly cold, a lifeless void that seems to drain warmth from your skin.
You touch it, and for a moment, the surface feels like liquid, trembling slightly.
Your fingertips meet no resistance at first—as though the window isn’t fully there.
The glass feels wrong, brittle and fragile yet unnaturally resistant to pressure.
As your hand lingers, an icy chill spreads through your fingertips, creeping up your arm.
